That's a good point and may be correct. On the other hand, it might just be just poor scaling of the image in the lower panel of the section 'Three possible models', but I am not 100% sure the three simulations are even done with the same stimulus (I'll check with Jing). On the other hand, for the panel "ECoG design and predictions", the three simulations use the same stimulus (single pulse of 500 ms) and the three plots are the same duration (1 s each). So that panel shows the clearest comparison of the outputs of the three models.\
\'a0\
- What is the form you assume for the neural IRF? For the fMRI data analysis, was tau1 fixed to some value? It strikes me that it would be difficult to measure this for your stimuli in fMRI data (although it is nicely measured in the ECoG).\
\
The IRF is assumed to be a gamma function: 
\f2\i t .* exp(-t/tau1)
\f1\i0 \
You are right that it is hard to infer tau1 from the fMRI experiment. I believe we assumed 50 ms for the fMRI data. Jing solved the fMRI models using many different fixed tau1s, and the pattern of results for the exponents is always the same - e.g., highest in V1, lowest in TO. But the numerical value of the exponents changes a little when you change tau1.\'a0 It is not impossible to fit with fMRI data but it is noisy. It would be impossible to fit with the fMRI data alone if the neural responses were linear, but the nonlinearity gives you a little power to fit the time constant. When do fit it, we get something non-crazy - shortest in V1 and longer in extrastriate areas. But it is quite noisy and not very reliable.\
\
\
- In the fMRI section (\'93CTS model accounts for temporal nonlinearities in fMRI data\'94) the fit of the CTS model is shown. It is sensible to me that the DN stage would not contribute much to the fits here given the brief duration of the stimuli with regard to the temporal scale of the HRF. Does this intuition match yours?\
\
Yes, that intuition matches mine. There is also another way to frame it that makes the differences between the models more explicit. The CTS model has the form X^n, with n less than 1 and X equal to the convolution of the stimulus time series with the IRF. This nonlinearity is pretty similar to X/(sigma + X) for appropriate values of sigma. In this sense, the CTS is really a normalization model with instantaneous normalization, and the DN model is the same but with a delay in the normalization. Since the fMRI response is slow, the exact timing of when the normalization kicks in doesn't have a big effect on the BOLD amplitude. I think this is similar to your point. For the manuscript, we might rewrite the CTS model in the form of instantaneous divisive normalization rather than a power law just for compatibility with the other model. (On the other hand, the power law is nice because it is similar to our compressive spatial summation power law). We'll see.\
